What is the structure of your dataset?¶

From the above sections, Initially, the dataset had 183,412 rows and 16 columns which were dropped to 174,952 rows and 22 columns after feature engineering of which are trips recorded in San Francisco Bay Area in 2019. It also contains 6 Floats, 2 datetime, 2 int and 12 object columns.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in exploring the trips durations, time of the day, day of the week, month of the year most trips were taken along with how they relate to the riders characteristics.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Each trip's start time and duration information will help in understanding how long a trip takes and when. The member information like user type, gender will help in finding out the main target groups (customer). Hence;

  • user_type
  • member_gender

    In [ ]:

    Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

    Duration: The duration distribution seemed higly aligned to the right at first suggesting a strong positively skewed distribution. This prompted us to plot the distribution using a log scale hence reducing the skew level. Later, it was evident that log scaling proved to be illuminating. It also made the distribution to become a unimodel and an approximate normal distribution.

    Time of day: It was evident that the plots had peaks in the morning hours i.e. 8AM and 9AM and evening hours i.e. 4PM - 6PM. This showed that more trips were made before and after office/working hours. A substanstial decline in trips recorded was observed in hours after 6PM.

    Week days: It was evident that more trips were made on Weekdays (Monday - Friday) as compared to weekends (Saturday - Sunday) and a high volume of trips were recorded on Thursdays.

    User type: It was evident that majority of the users are Subscribers with a substantial difference to Customers.

    Gender: It was evident, that majority of the users are Male with Substantial difference to Female users. An insignificant number of trips belog to Other gender type

    Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

    We discovered that the durations i.e. start_time and end_time were having incorrect data type. We later changed their data types to datetime using the pandas datetime convention function.

    We also analysed a feature outside our area of interest i.e. Bikes Share for all trip and it was evident that majority of the users did not use bike share for their trips.

    Bivariate Exploration¶

    In [32]:
    def plot_hist_bivariates(figsize, variables, main_variable, unicolored, ylabel, **kwargs):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(len(variables), figsize = figsize)
    
    # ploting relationships
    count = 0
    for var in variables:
        color = 'Blues' if count % 2 == 0 else 'Greens'
        if unicolored and kwargs.get('type') == 'bar':
            sb.barplot(data = bikes_df_clean, x = var, y = main_variable, ax=ax[count], palette=color);
        elif not unicolored and kwargs.get('type') == 'bar':
            sb.barplot(data = bikes_df_clean, x = var, y = main_variable, ax=ax[count]);
#         if unicolored and kwargs.get('type') == 'box':
#             sb.boxplot(data = bikes_df_clean, x = var, y = main_variable, ax=ax[count], palette=color, showfliers=False);
#         elif not unicolored and kwargs.get('type') == 'box':
#             sb.boxplot(data = bikes_df_clean, x = var, y = main_variable, ax=ax[count], showfliers=False);
        elif unicolored:
            sb.countplot(data = bikes_df_clean, x = var, hue = main_variable, ax=ax[count], palette=color);
        else:
            sb.countplot(data = bikes_df_clean, x = var, hue = main_variable, ax=ax[count]);
            
        ax[count].set_ylabel(ylabel);
        x_label = var.replace('_', ' ').title();
        y_label = main_variable.replace('_', ' ').title();
        title =  'Relationship between ' + ylabel + ' and '+ x_label if kwargs.get('type') == 'bar' else  'Relationship between ' + x_label + ' and '+ y_label ;
        ax[count].set_xlabel(x_label);
        ax[count].set_title(title);
        count = count + 1
        
    fig.tight_layout();

    Conclusions¶

    From the analysis made above, the following observations were made;

  • Most trips were made on Thursdays and Tuesdays.
  • Weekends had least trips recorded.
  • Most trips about 90% were made by Subscribers.
  • Most Trips were made by Male
  • Weekend Trips had longer durations as compared to weekday trips
  • Casual Customers spent more trip duration as compared to subscribers
  • Female Customers made the most trip durations than Males

    • Limitations¶

    Below are some of the limitations experienced during this analysis;

  • Given the limited time, a partial analysis was made on the dataset. More variables can be explored and visualizations can be drawn from them.
  • The dataset had only a few months i.e February and March from 2019. Hence if more data was provided, interesting conclusions could be made.
